kshire, England":"Ripon, Jórvík, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1387–1439":"1387–1439","1385–1437":"1385–1437","1401–1460":"1401–1460","1437":"1437","1401":"1401","1387":"1387","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1439":"1439","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ripon, Yorkshire, England":"Ripon, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1387–1439":"1387–1439","1385–1437":"1385–1437","1401–1460":"1401–1460","1437":"1437","1401":"1401","1387":"1387","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1439":"1439","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Ripon, Yorkshire, England":"Ripon, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Plumton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called with Old English <i>plūme</i>, <i>plȳme</i> ‘plum, plum tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, including Plumpton (Yorkshire, Northamptonshire, Sussex, Cumbria), Fieldplumpton or Woodplumpton (Lancashire), Plympton (Devon), and a lost <i>Plumpton</i> in Kingsbury (Warwicks)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Plumton was born in 1387, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 daughters with Richard Fennel ,of Winslow. She died in 1439, in her hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1387–1439":"1387–1439","1385–1437":"1385–1437","1401–1460":"1401–1460","1437":"1437","1401":"1401","1387":"1387","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1439":"1439","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, Unite